docs.abstract: On Oct. 26, 1958, the airline made a historic flight from New York to Paris that helped usher in the jet age.
docs.snippet: On Oct. 26, 1958, the airline made a historic flight from New York to Paris that helped usher in the jet age.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Oct. 26, 1958, Pan American World Airways made the first commercial nonstop flight from New York to Paris. A marching band played John Philip Sousa as guests boarded the plane, where 111 passengers supped on cuisine from Maxim’s in Paris. Twenty-five years later, the airline commemorated the voyage by inviting celebrities like Eartha Kitt and the boxing champ Floyd Patterson to Paris in one of the original Boeing 707 jets. Once there, the crew was feted at a party.

headline.main: Pan Am Remains Grounded. In Culture, That Is.
headline.print_headline: How Pan Am Extended Aura of Jet Travel to All

docs.lead_paragraph: JAKARTA, Indonesia — The fatal crash of Lion Air Flight 610 last year was caused by systemic design flaws in the Boeing 737 Max that were compounded by flight crew lapses, Indonesian investigators told the relatives of victims on Wednesday.
